│ The bug is an assertion failure in the loop vectorizer, indicating a disagreement between  │
│ the VPlan cost model and the legacy cost model. The root cause is that the VPlan cost      │
│ model fails to correctly account for the "widening store" optimization pattern (`load i8`, │
│ `zext i8 to i32`, `store i32`), leading to an inaccurate cost calculation compared to the  │
│ legacy model.                                                                              │
│                                                                                            │
│ My plan to fix this is to enhance the VPlan's `getInstructionCost` function to recognize   │
│ this specific pattern. When a `StoreInst` is encountered, I will check if its value        │
│ operand is a `ZExtInst`. If this pattern is confirmed to be a widening store by the        │
│ existing `isWideningStore` helper function, I will calculate the store's cost based on the │
│ *source type* of the `zext` instruction. This change will align the VPlan cost model with  │
│ the legacy model's more accurate costing for this case, resolving the discrepancy and the  │
│ assertion failure.                                                                         │
│                                                                                            │
│ I will now implement this fix.                                                             │
